    <h1>Kan Extensions</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski &middot; 2017 &middot; <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2017/04/17/kan-extensions/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 21</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-16/">&#x1F35E; Ch16 (Adjunctions)</a>, Ch20 (Ends and Coends). 12 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">"All concepts are Kan extensions" (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saunders_Mac_Lane"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Mac Lane</a>). Given functors K : I &rarr; A and D : I &rarr; C, the <strong>right Kan extension</strong> Ran<sub>K</sub>D : A &rarr; C is the best approximation of D along K. It answers: how do you extend a functor defined on a subcategory to the whole category? Limits, colimits, and adjunctions are all special cases.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. The problem: extending a functor -->
    <h3>The problem: extending a functor</h3>
    <p>You have a functor D : I &rarr; C that maps a small category I into C. You also have a functor K : I &rarr; A that embeds I into a larger category A. You want to extend D to all of A, not just the image of K. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kan_extension"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Kan extension</a> is the universal solution: the best functor A &rarr; C that approximates D, given K.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Setup: I is a small subcategory, A is the full category.
; K embeds I into A.  D maps I into values (our target).
; Goal: extend D to all of A, not just where K lands.
;
; Concrete example:
; I = {mon, tue}    (two days we have data for)
; A = {mon, tue, wed, thu, fri}  (full work week)
; K embeds mon->mon, tue->tue
; D maps mon->10, tue->20  (sales on those days)
;
; Right Kan extension: conservative estimate for wed, thu, fri.
; Left Kan extension: liberal estimate.

(define I '(mon tue))
(define A '(mon tue wed thu fri))

; D: the functor we know (defined on I)
(define (D day)
  (cond ((eq? day 'mon) 10)
        ((eq? day 'tue) 20)
        (else (begin (display "ERROR: D is only defined on I") (newline)))))

; K: the embedding I -> A (identity on the subcategory)
(define (K day) day)

(display "D(mon) = ") (display (D 'mon)) (newline)
(display "D(tue) = ") (display (D 'tue)) (newline)
(display "D is not defined on wed, thu, fri.") (newline)
(display "Kan extensions fill in those gaps.")
`} />

    <!-- 2. Right Kan extension -->
    <h3>Right Kan extension: the conservative approximation</h3>
    <p>The <strong>right Kan extension</strong> Ran<sub>K</sub>D comes with a natural transformation &epsilon; : Ran<sub>K</sub>D &#8728; K &rarr; D. It is universal: for any other functor F with &epsilon;' : F &#8728; K &rarr; D, there is a unique &sigma; : F &rarr; Ran<sub>K</sub>D such that &epsilon;' factors through &epsilon;. In Set, it is computed as an end: Ran<sub>K</sub>D(a) = &int;<sub>i</sub> Set(A(a, Ki), Di). Read this as: "for each object a in A, consider all morphisms from a into the image of K, and use them to probe D."</p>

